That translates to good news for Morgan Stanley, Bank of
America, Barclays, Mizuho, MUFG, Soci=C3=A9t=C3=A9 G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale, and =
BNP Paribas, who can now move this debt off their balance sheets and make r=
oom for the next round of leveraged loans. There=E2=80=99s still the $4 bil=
lion of junior X debt that will likely remain on their balance sheets for t=
he time being. But they might as well wait and see what happens at this poi=
nt, right?

=C2=A0

As for the $31 billion of equity, things seem to be
looking up on that front, too, albeit slowly. Using the $20 billion enterpr=
ise valuation, that would mean the X equity is now worth around $7 billion =
(after subtracting the $13 billion of debt at par), or 77.5 percent less th=
an the original $31 billion of equity invested. That pretty much squares wi=
th the price that one Fidelity fund with a $19.7 million stake in X valued =
its position as in November: $5.8 million, a decrease of 71 percent from th=
e original value of the investment, but up from a
valuation of $5.5 million in October.

=C2=A0

Of course, there are at least a few skeptics of this suddenly rosy scenario=
=2E On Bluesky, Kara Swisher referred t=
o the payments from xAI to X for its d=
ata as =E2=80=9Ccircular accounting nonsense.=E2=80=9D Another source claim=
ed that Elon =E2=80=9Cjust moved money from one pocket to the other, to mak=
e it look profitable so he could sell the debt,=E2=80=9D and that user grow=
th is =E2=80=9Cstagnant,=E2=80=9D revenue is
=E2=80=9Chorrible,=E2=80=9D and Linda is =E2=80=9Ca clown.=E2=80=9D Is this=
 skepticism or schadenfreude? I haven=E2=80=99t a clue. But the debt is mov=
ing, and at prices that would=E2=80=99ve seemed implausible six months ago.=
 Regardless of how Elon did it, the debt syndication clearly seems to have =
worked out for the banks, and for some of the first wave of investors who b=
ought that debt.

We=E2=80=99re still far from a payday for Elon=E2=80=99s fellow equity inve=
stors, such as a16z, Larry
Ellison, and the Saudi billionaire Prince Alwaleed. But between the sale of=
 a majority of the debt for nearly par, the A.I. valuation euphoria, the in=
creasing EBITDA, and the ongoing Elon-Trump bromance (like other media comp=
anies, X recently settled its lawsuit with Trump for booting him off the pl=
atform, pre-Elon, because of January 6), the first glimmers of hope in more=
 than two years are starting to emerge for this deal, once considered one
of the worst made after the 2008 financial crisis. I have to admit, I didn=
=E2=80=99t see that coming.

