=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">That translates to good news for Morgan St=
anley, Bank of
America, Barclays, Mizuho, MUFG, Soci=C3=A9t=C3=A9 G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale, and =
BNP Paribas, who can now move this debt off their balance sheets and make r=
oom for the next round of leveraged loans. There=E2=80=99s still the $4 bil=
lion of junior X debt that will likely remain on their balance sheets for t=
he time being. But they might as well wait and see what happens at this poi=
nt, right?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As for the $31 billion of equity, things s=
eem to be
looking up on that front, too, albeit slowly. Using the $20 billion enterpr=
ise valuation, that would mean the X equity is now worth around $7 billion =
(after subtracting the $13 billion of debt at par), or 77.5 percent less th=
an the original $31 billion of equity invested. That pretty much squares wi=
th the price that one Fidelity fund with a $19.7 million stake in X valued =
its position as in November: $5.8 million, a decrease of 71 percent from th=
e original value of the investment, but up from a
valuation of $5.5 million in October.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Of course, there =
are at least a few skeptics of this suddenly rosy scenario. On Bluesky, Kar=
a Swisher referred to the payments from xAI to X for its data as =E2=80=9Cc=
ircular accounting nonsense.=E2=80=9D Another source claimed that Elon =E2=
=80=9Cjust moved money from one pocket to the other, to make it look profit=
able so he could sell the debt,=E2=80=9D and that user growth is =E2=80=9Cs=
tagnant,=E2=80=9D revenue is
=E2=80=9Chorrible,=E2=80=9D and Linda is =E2=80=9Ca clown.=E2=80=9D Is this=
 skepticism or <em>schadenfreude</em>? I haven=E2=80=99t a clue. But the de=
bt is moving, and at prices that would=E2=80=99ve seemed implausible six mo=
nths ago. Regardless of <em>how</em> Elon did it, the debt syndication clea=
rly seems to have worked out for the banks, and for some of the first wave =
of investors who bought that debt.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>We=E2=80=
=99re still far from a payday for Elon=E2=80=99s fellow equity investors, s=
uch as a16z, <strong>Larry</strong>
<strong>Ellison</strong>, and the Saudi billionaire <strong>Prince</strong>=
 <strong>Alwaleed</strong>. But between the sale of a majority of the debt =
for nearly par, the A.I. valuation euphoria, the increasing EBITDA, and the=
 ongoing Elon-Trump bromance (like other media companies, X recently settle=
d its lawsuit with Trump for booting him off the platform, pre-Elon, becaus=
e of January 6), the first glimmers of hope in more than two years are star=
ting to emerge for this deal, once considered one
of the worst made after the 2008 financial crisis. I have to admit, I didn=
=E2=80=99t see that coming.</p></div>
